AB  - Material ecocriticism is an apt approach for interpreting Anthropocene narratives. From this perspective, non-humans as well as humans are seen as fully fledged actors; the world’s materiality appears as a combined ‘mesh’ in which the emerging dynamics of body and identity, nature and culture, bios and society are seen to be interacting with and can also be examined through one another. Through the lens of material ecocriticism, this paper explores the agency of nature and the human in climate change through two contemporary Chinese literary works.
