AB  - As concerns over climate change grow there has been some debate as to whether, despite being increasingly ecologically aware, liberal-capitalist societies are conceptually equipped to deal with the current ecological situation. Moreover, it has been suggested that ecocriticism itself is underpinned by a methodological liberalism which can make it blind to certain problems and contradictions within its own methods and focuses. Taking these issues as its starting point, this essay reads a variety of texts, particularly the work of Derek Mahon, to explore how irony can function as a tool for exposing contradictions within environmentalist thought and practice. However, it also suggests that the kind of ironic disposition we find in contemporary writing about ecology sometimes risks morphing into a morbid cynicism.
