AB  - This dissertation project explores the way advocates in the United States have come to the realization of a sense of loss as a result of water crises and are imagining new possibilities for living with water that are healthier. In particular, I am interested in how specific activists are articulating a sense of loss of water - as essential to life, a source of livelihood, and an essential element shaping broader cultural and ecological systems - in ways that might provide indications not only of choices that have failed us in the past, but also those that could help sustain our lives in the future. As such, my overarching research question is: +how does the rhetorical commemoration of water offer a productive way of amplifying contemporary ecological and climate crises, as well as articulate more viable possibilities for civic life?= In order to explore, and answer this question, I rhetorically analyze three texts. The first is the documentary, +Chasing Ice.= Then, I focus on the website for the environmental group, +Raise the River. Citation reproduced with permission of ProQuest LLC. Abridged abstract reproduced with permission of ProQuest LLC. Full text available at URL below.
