AB  - Part of the impasse we face in discussing climate change is that to speak on behalf of a beleaguered planet we need to mean too much. But if the Anthropocene names the era of man-made climate, it is also the era of the exhaustion of humanistic purpose, in which science has lost much of its normative social authority even as its warnings of global crisis become increasingly dire, and since 9/11 ethical norms generally have been increasingly undermined by global corporate capitalism and the War on Terror. The iconic Romantic period lyrics explored here - by Smith, Wordsworth, Byron and Keats - suggest how this debilitation of restrictive, normative economies might teach us how to mean less, to consume less meaning, by framing speech in Latour's sense as prosthesis, and speaking, with de Man, as personification. Perhaps counter to common conceptions of both Bataille and Romanticism, such lyric engages excess as a sublimity of frequency rather than amplitude, undermining anthropocentrism not by pretending to exceed it (such pretense is after all anthropocentrism's signature), but by a 'post-personal personification' that endlessly rehearses anthropocentric form for its own sake.
