AB  - This dissertation interrogates how people have used language to create responses to past and present crises associated with climate change, global warming, and the over-use of resources in ways that are meaningful to their own lived realities; it is a rhetorical study of the evolution of interpretations of sustainability in the United States from the late 20th century to the early 21st century. I contribute to the growing literature on sustainability through three case studies of political debates over the environment that took place in Oregon beginning in the 1970s and continue to this day. To do so, I use four major theoretical lenses that stretch across all of its inquiries into sustainability discourse: 1) a 'rhetorical-historical' lens, which examines the discursive history of sustainability movements; 2) a strictly rhetorical approach that relies on Aristotelian and other classical terms; 3) a public sphere/publics lens, which not only interrogates discourse's place within theories of local and global communities, but also addresses the problems of American democratic liberalism; 4) and, a literacy and discourse lens, which situates the work in the field of Composition and Rhetoric. These theoretical lenses, combined with historical case studies, create a frame through which the following commonly-asked question may be answered: why is it that environmental rhetoric is not often taken up by its intended publics? I find throughout these case studies that the concept of sustainability values an Aristotelian 'common good,' which inherently runs up against the autonomy valued by postwar liberalism. At the same time, such a view often rejects dissenting voices because it sees compromise as unethical, which creates sustainability discourses that are unable to integrate minority opinions. Citation reproduced with permission of ProQuest LLC. Abridged abstract reproduced with permission of ProQuest LLC. Full text available at URL below.
