AB  - Recent debates over the ‘securitisation’ of climate change have underlined the importance of exploring the links between modern forms of warfare and environmental crisis. However, their elusive complexity suggests what has been called ‘a crisis of intelligibility’ (Chamayou 2015, 14). Nevertheless, growing numbers of novelists have sought to engage with climate change, whilst war has always been a prominent literary theme. The aim of this article is, therefore, to evaluate a range of novels that, under the guise of speculative fiction, engage (if sometimes obliquely) with the interplay of conflict and environmental crisis. In doing so, the article considers whether conventional literary modes are capable of encompassing the relationship between humans and the environment in time of war, or whether the very failure of those modes opens up a space within which new and more effective modes of representation are possible.
