AB  - This paper argues that J. G. Ballard’s The Drowned World presents an ethical call to commit to a project oriented towards egalitarianism and justice that attends to the ways that racialisation and colonial violence condition and are perpetuated by the capitalist system that has caused ecological collapse. I demonstrate that the noisy geographical atmosphere of the novel, in which consciousness and landscape share a devolution caused by non-anthropogenic climate change, models what I am calling an ‘eco-racial disaster’ perhaps useful to ecocritical studies of the Anthropocene. This disaster is the traumatic idea of a non-anthropocentric reality that puts pressure on the links between subject and object and ultimately introduces a differentiation into the universalising Anthropos of the Anthropocene. It may be further defined as a form of colonial violence independent of phenomenology, or a haunting that is a reminder that racialisation animates the way one thinks about ecological crisis.
