AB  - The aim of this article is to re-evaluate J. G. Ballard’s first novel, The Wind from Nowhere, from the perspective of Timothy Morton’s theory of the hyperobject. According to Morton, hyperobjects are entities that, like climate change, challenge the human ability to conceptualise and represent them. Ballard’s novel depicts a world overwhelmed by a steadily strengthening wind that itself resembles the footprint of a hyperobject. However, Ballard’s strategy for representing the impact of the hyperobject risks turning the novel into a conventional example of disaster-oriented fiction. Confronted by a phenomenon of such apocalyptic severity, his characters have few options. Nonetheless, Ballard’s approach problematises Morton’s prediction of a future in which humankind cares for the hyperobject, whilst anticipating the emergence of a new form of ‘weird’ realism perhaps better able to render life in the time of hyperobjects.
