AB  - This essay explores ‘indigenous’ and ‘western’ forms of the sacred through the case of the Sámi in the northern fringes of Europe. The focus is on sonic images, ritual performance, shamanic drum practice and animal symbolism in the film Ofelaš (Pathfinder 1987). The essay explores how this film represents and affirms indigenous sacrality, reinscribes the dualities of indigenous–western and reifies ethnic politics in the northernmost regions of modern Nordic nation-states. Ultimately, the exploration moves beyond the micro-dynamics of polar politics to look at the film's wider relevance. In privileging sonic expression and its spectres, I read the film as contributing to critical perspectives on authority, knowledge, history, oral tradition and climate change in postcolonial thinking.
