AB  - A fortunate confluence of literary and political currents created in France the atmosphere for a favorable reception of the early works of Melville. Under the influence of the romantics, criticism in the first years of the decade 1846 to 1856 welcomed with exuberant curiosity the new and the foreign. Furthermore, French dissatisfaction with their own recent governments aroused interest in America, its people as well as its political system. For these reasons Melville's works were reviewed in well-known periodicals by eminent critics such as Philarète Chasles. His commentators, while enjoying Melville's vivid descriptions of adventures in exotic lands, also sought in his writings an explanation of the American character. In the closing years of the decade, however, the authoritarian regime of Napoleon III brought about a sharp change in the intellectual and political climate. Melville's popularity suffered because of the new conservatism in literature led by Sainte-Beuve and because of the obscurity of some of his later works. The author of +Moby-Dick= sunk into oblivion until after World War I.
